\section{\code{nrow_max}}{
\code{nrow_max} is the \emph{sample}-level \strong{simulation setting}: the fixed size of
the shared \code{sample} draw that every \code{nrow} value sub-truncates
(\code{head(sample, nrow)}, \code{TARGETS-DESIGN.md} section 5). The effective
per-dataset draw is \code{min(nrow_max, nrow(data))} for \code{replace = FALSE} (the
high default thus draws the full permutation) and \code{nrow_max} rows for
\code{replace = TRUE}. Because the draw size is fixed - not derived from
\code{max(nrow)} - adding \code{nrow} values (within the effective draw size) never
changes the draw, so cached \code{sample} shards stay valid. Each \code{nrow} is
validated at construction against the effective draw size. It is not
\code{ci}-gated (the draw happens regardless of \code{ci}) and, like \code{dists} and
\code{est_method}, it is absent from \code{task_axes("sample")}, so it never
multiplies tasks or enters the per-task RNG primer.
}

\section{\code{ci}}{
\code{ci} is a scalar flag (not a cross-join axis): the point estimate \code{est} is
invariant to \code{ci} - it is computed analytically from the fit, independent of
the bootstrap and RNG - so a single \code{ci = TRUE} run is a strict superset of
\code{ci = FALSE} (same \code{est}, plus the \code{se}/\code{lcl}/\code{ucl} columns). The choice is
scenario-wide either/or: \code{ci = FALSE} for cheap, bootstrap-free point
estimates, or \code{ci = TRUE} for estimates plus confidence intervals. When
\code{ci = FALSE}, the bootstrap-only knobs \code{nboot}, \code{ci_method}, and \code{parametric}
are meaningless; passing any of them in that case is an error, so set
\code{ci = TRUE} to enable bootstrap, or omit the knobs.
}

\section{\code{dists} and \code{est_method}}{
\code{dists} and \code{est_method} are \strong{simulation settings}, not cross-join axes -
they are absent from \code{task_axes("fit")}/\code{task_axes("hc")}, so they never
multiply tasks or enter the per-task RNG primer. \code{dists} is the \emph{fit}-level
setting: the whole character vector is handed to one \code{ssd_fit_dists()} call
per fit task (fanning out per distribution would dissolve the model averaging
that defines a fit). \code{est_method} is an \emph{hc}-level setting: every requested
